wie: David Live / Stage |publisher=Pitchforkmedia |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060830011741/http://www.pitchforkmedia.com/article/record_review/15619/David_Bowie_David_Live_Stage |archive-date=30 August 2006 }}</ref>\n| rev8 = ''[[The Rolling Stone Album Guide]]''\n| rev8Score =  {{Rating|3.5|5}}<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/artists/david-bowie/albumguide |title=David Bowie: Album Guide |magazine=[[Rolling Stone|rollingstone.com]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110530073307/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/artists/david-bowie/albumguide |archivedate=30 May 2011 |accessdate=13 January 2016}}</ref>\n| rev9 = ''[[Select (magazine)|Select]]''\n| rev9score = 4/5<ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://selectmagazinescans.monkeon.co.uk/showpage.php?file=wp-content/uploads/2014/10/reissues.jpg |title=David Bowie: Stage |date=March 1992 |accessdate=11 September 2017 |magazine= [[Select (magazine)|Select]] |last=Collis |first=Andrew |page=75 }}</ref>\n| rev10 = ''[[Uncut (magazine)|Uncut]]''\n| rev10Score =  {{Rating|3|5}}<ref name=\"Roberts/Uncut\">{{cite magazine|first=Chris|last=Roberts|title=David Bowie ''Stage''|magazine=[[Uncut (magazine)|Uncut]] |date=April 2005|p=130}}</ref>\n}}\n'''''Stage''''' is the second [[live album]] by English musician [[David Bowie]], recorded on the [[Isolar II \u2013 The 1978 World Tour|Isolar II Tour]], and released by [[RCA Records]] in 1978. First UK pressings were on translucent yellow vinyl and some European pressings were also available on blue vinyl. Though it was rumoured {{cn|date=February 2019}}at the time that this would be his final outing with the label, following dissatisfaction over the promotion of ''[[Low (David Bowie album)|Low]]'' and ''[[\"Heroes\" (David Bowie album)|\"Heroes\"]]'', Bowie remained with RCA until 1982.\n\n==Recording==\nThe recording was culled from concerts in [[Philadelphia]], [[Providence, Rhode Island|Providence]] and [[Boston]], US, in late April and early May 1978. It primarily included material from Bowie's most recent studio albums to that date, ''[[Station to Station]]'', ''Low'' and ''\"Heroes\"'' but also five songs from ''[[The Rise and Fall of Ziggy Stardust and the Spiders from Mars]]''. Aside from Bowie's core team of [[Carlos Alomar]], [[Dennis Davis]] and [[George Murray (musician)|George Murray]], band members included ex-[[Frank Zappa]] sideman [[Adrian Belew]] on guitar, [[Simon House]] from [[Hawkwind]] on electric violin, [[Roger Powell (musician)|Roger Powell]], best known for his work with [[Todd Rundgren]] in the group [[Utopia (band)|Utopia]], on keyboards and [[Sean Mayes]] on piano, string ensemble and backup vocals. All would reunite the following year on Bowie's next studio LP, ''[[Lodger (album)|Lodger]]''.\n\nAs Bowie rarely tampered with the arrangements \u2013 in contrast to his method on ''David Live'' \u2013 ''Stage'' added little to what was available on the original albums, and was seen by some commentators as simply a marketing exercise that did not do justice to a memorable series of live concerts. Even the cover picture came in for criticism, more so because the rest of the package contained only variations of the same shot.\n\n==Reception==\n''Stage'' was a commercial success. In the UK, it reached No. 5 and was subsequently certified gold by the [[British Phonographic Industry|British Phonographic Industry (BPI)]]. It also reached No. 44 on the US charts.\n\n\"[[Breaking Glass (song)|Breaking Glass]]\", which originally appeared in shorter form on ''[[Low (David Bowie album)|Low]]'', was released as a 3-track [[Extended play|EP]] and reached number 54 on the UK singles chart. In the US, \"[[Star (David Bowie song)|Star]]\" was released as a 3-track EP, but failed to chart. In Japan \"[[Soul Love (David Bowie song)|Soul Love]]\" was released, with \"Blackout\" on the B-side, but also failed to chart.\n\nGenerally considered more relaxed than Bowie's previous live album, ''[[David Live]]'', ''Stage'' was praised on its initial vinyl release for the fidelity with which the band was able to emulate in concert the electronic and effects-filled numbers from ''Low'' and ''\"Heroes\"'', as well as for the singer's vocal performance. However, it was criticised for lacking a 'live' atmosphere, thanks to the recording being largely taken from direct instrument and microphone feeds which increased sound quality but minimised crowd noise. The original concert running order was also changed, with fades between tracks similar to a studio album. In a review of the 1991 rerelease, Mat Snow of ''[[Q (magazine)|Q]]'' stated that \"performances are faster than the studio originals and suffer for it; what they gain in live jauntiness \u2013 not exactly a quality they were crying out for \u2013 they lose in power and intensity.\"<ref>Snow, Mat (March 1992), [[Q (magazine)|Q]]</ref>\n\nA 2005 reissue saw many of the criticisms of the original LP addressed. In his review of the reissue, Chris Roberts of ''[[Uncut (magazine)|Uncut]]'' said that the combination of ''Low''/''Heroes''-period material and songs from ''Ziggy Stardust'' resulted in a live album that was an \"eerie clattering between two stools\". He said that the improvements in sound carried out by [[Tony Visconti]] and the addition of \"Stay\" and \"the brilliant 'Be My Wife'\" made the new version of ''Stage'' \"essential for Dave-freaks, anyway\".<ref name=\"Roberts/Uncut\" />\n\nThe album is included in [[The Quietus]]' list of its writers' \"40 Favourite Live Albums\".<ref>{{cite web |title=The Quietus Writers' 40 Favourite Live Albums |author=John Doran |date=5 February 2013 |website=The Quietus |url=http://thequietus.com/articles/11293-best-live-albums}}</ref>\n\n==Track listings==\nAll tracks written by [[David Bowie]], except where noted.\n\n===Original 1978 LP===\n\n{{tracklist\n| all_writing     = \n| collapsed       = no\n| headline        =Side one\n| total_length    = 16:22\n| title1          = [[Hang On to Yourself]]\n| length1         = 3:26\n| title2          = [[Ziggy Stardust (song)|Ziggy Stardust]]\n| length2         = 3:32\n| title3          = [[Five Years (David Bowie song)|Five Years]]\n| length3         = 3:58\n| title4          = [[Soul Love (David Bowie song)|Soul Love]]\n| length4         = 2:55\n| title5          = Star\n| length5         = 2:31\n}}\n\n{{tracklist\n| all_writing     = \n| collapsed       = no\n| headline        =Side two\n| total_length    = 17:38\n| title1          = [[Station to Station (song)|Station to Station]]\n| length1         = 8:55\n| title2          = [[Fame (David Bowie song)|Fame]]\n| note2           = Bowie, [[Carlos Alomar]], [[John Lennon]]\n| length2         = 4:06\n| title3          = [[TVC 15]]\n| length3         = 4:37\n}}\n\n{{tracklist\n| all_writing     = \n| collapsed       = no\n| headline        =Side three\n| total_length    = 19:25\n| title1          = [[Warszawa (song)|Warszawa]]\n| note1           = Bowie, [[Brian Eno]]\n| length1         = 6:50\n| title2         = [[Speed of Life (David Bowie song)|Speed of Life]]\n| length2        = 2:44\n| title3         = [[Art Decade]]\n| length3        = 3:10\n| title4         = [[Sense of Doubt]]\n| length4        = 3:13\n| title5         = [[Breaking Glass (song)|Breaking Glass]]\n| note5          = Bowie, [[Dennis Davis]], [[George Murray (musician)|George Murray]]\n| length5        = 3:28\n}}\n\n{{tracklist\n| all_writing     = \n| collapsed       = no\n| headline        =Side four\n| total_length    = 19:52 (73:17)\n| title1         = [[\"Heroes\" (David Bowie song)|\"Heroes\"]]\n| note1          = Bowie, Eno\n| length1        = 6:19\n| title2         = [[What in the World]]\n| length2        = 4:24\n| title3         = [[Blackout (David Bowie song)|Blackout]]\n| length3        = 4:01\n| title4         = [[Beauty and the Beast (David Bowie song)|Beauty and the Beast]]\n| length4        = 5:08\n}}\nThe cassette release places \"[[Speed of Life (David Bowie song)|Speed of Life]]\" between \"Fame\" and \"TVC 15\".\n\n===Rereleases===\n''Stage'' has been rereleased on CD four times to date, the first being in 1984 by [[RCA Records]], then in 1991 by [[Rykodisc]] (containing a bonus track), later in 2005 by [[EMI]], and most recently in 2017 by [[Parlophone]] (also on vinyl). The running order of the 2005 and 2017 editions reflects the actual performance, removing fades between tracks, and including previously unreleased performances as bonus tracks.\n\nThe 2005 [[EMI]] release of this album was [[Copy protection|copy protected]] with [[Cactus Data Shield|CDS 200]] in the EU.\n\n====1984 rerelease====\nThe 1984 rerelease on CD (catalogue number PD89002) contains the same running order as the original LP, and comes on two discs (despite the double-LP release being short enough to fit on a single CD unaltered). Some of the European-distributed CDs were manufactured in Japan, but cover and assembling were made in Europe. Most of the CDs were made in Germany.\n\n====1991 rerelease track listing====\n\nIn 1991, Stage was rereleased on CD, with the same running order as the original LP, with \"[[Alabama Song#David Bowie version|Alabama Song]]\" included as a bonus track.\n{{tracklist\n| all_writing     = \n| collapsed       = yes\n| headline        =CD one\n| total_length    = 34:00\n| title1          = Hang On to Yourself\n| length1         = 3:26\n| title2          = Ziggy Stardust\n| length2         = 3:32\n| title3          = Five Years\n| length3         = 3:58\n| title4          = Soul Love\n| length4         = 2:55\n| title5          = Star\n| length5         = 2:31\n| title6          = Station to Station\n| length6         = 8:55\n| title7          = Fame\n| writer7         = Bowie, Alomar, Lennon\n| length7         = 4:06\n| title8          = TVC 15\n| length8         = 4:37\n}}\n\n{{tracklist\n| all_writing     = \n| collapsed       = yes\n| headline        =CD two\n| total_length    = 4